## Here's the plan

**Only one file needs to change: `src/routes.ts`.**

### What I found

| File | Key detail |
|------|------------|
| `src/routes.ts` | `GET /users` returns `res.json(users)` — flat array, no envelope |
| `src/data.ts` | 15 in-memory users (IDs 1–15) |
| `src/types.ts` | `User { id, name, email, role }` |
| `tests/routes.test.ts` | **Already has all 4 pagination tests** — they're failing now |

### The change

Replace the `GET /users` handler with:

```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start      = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(start, start + limit);

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

**Key notes:**
- `parseInt(...) || 1` / `|| 10` handles missing/invalid query params with correct defaults
- `Array.slice` on an out-of-range `start` index naturally returns `[]` — no special-case needed for page=100
- The `GET /users/:id` endpoint is untouched
- All 6 tests (4 new pagination + 2 existing single-user) will pass after this
